Maybe its possible to do this:<br /><br /><ol style="list-style-type: decimal"><li>Mount your USB to a Different Drive Letter, far down the line, no other computer is likely to have, like S:\</li><li>Install a Second Version of Classic Shell into a new Master Folder, onto your USB Drive on S:\</li><li>Copy all of the Custom commands, linked items &amp; programs etc from other drives onto the same S:\ drive, into the same Master Folder as Classic Shell</li><li>Fix all of the links in the Menu from your current Classic Shell to Point to all S:\ Drives (it might be easier to re-create the folder hierarchy from your other drives on the S:\ Drive as well, so you can just change the Drive letter, and leave the rest of the path the same.. so they are basically just empty folders with copies of anything portable Classic Shell Menu links to, such as &quot;S:\Program Files\Portable Tools&quot; to copy an item from your main install drive, or &quot;S:\Computing\My Bat Files&quot; to copy all the bat files found in your &quot;Computing\My bat Files&quot; folder on your F:\ Drive, for example..</li><li>Create an *ISO image file of your S:\ Drive as it is, with a Drive/Folder/Any-to-ISO program</li><li>Save the .ISO File on the USB Drive at the top level along with a Drive-assignable ISO Mounter</li><li>Plug in your USB on the new computer, browse to the ISO file, Mount it to S:\ and double-click to start Classic Shell Menu</li><li>Any data you created or edited would be saved, so long as your menu included links to permanent folder locations on your USB, or even links to the files themselves would work, if they were never moved or renamed</li></ol><div align="right">-</div><br /><br />I wonder if this would work<br /><br />I wonder if theres a Stand-alone program that can mount ISO images to a selectable Drive letter, without Administrative Privileges<br /><br />or a way to always identify your USB as S:\, no matter where its plugged in, perhaps through a Firmware utility<br /><br />then we could create &amp; distribute custom ISO's for Portable use...<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://www.classicshell.net/forum/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=359">Tenzen</a> — Thu Apr 18, 2013 6:44 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
